<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,1484,1941]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,289,1484,1509]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Biology</emphasis>
: A female was found to have six embryos (
<bibRefCitation box="[819,996,1484,1509]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref31502" refString="Atallah, S. I. &amp; Harrison, D. L. (1967) New records of rodents, bats and insectivores from the Arabian Peninsula. Journal of Zoology, London, 153 (3), 311 - 319. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1967. tb 04065. x" type="journal article">Atallah, 1967b</bibRefCitation>
). In the Negev, two distinct breeding periods were observed, one in the spring and the second in late summer. In comparison with other species of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[223,329,1556,1581]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[223,329,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Gerbillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Winton" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[343,455,1556,1581]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="henleyi">
<emphasis box="[343,455,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">G. henleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more a seed eater, more mobile with a less stable home range than 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1240,1371,1556,1581]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dasyurus">
<emphasis box="[1240,1371,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">G. dasyurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This suggests that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Winton" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[307,421,1592,1617]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="henleyi">
<emphasis box="[307,421,1592,1617]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">G. henleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more adapted to xeric habitats than other gerbils (Shenbrot 
<emphasis box="[1148,1213,1592,1617]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">et al.,</emphasis>
1994). The pygmy gerbil is the smallest rodent known to inhabit the Jordanian deserts. It was collected from the Hammada areas with scarce vegetation cover. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Winton" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[435,549,1664,1689]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="henleyi">
<emphasis box="[435,549,1664,1689]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">G. henleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is mostly associated with the sand jird, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sundevall" authorityYear="1842" box="[1019,1218,1665,1688]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Meriones" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="crassus">
<emphasis box="[1019,1218,1665,1688]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Meriones crassus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the three-toed Jerboa, 
<taxonomicName authority="jaculus (Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2003 a)" authorityName="Abu Baker &amp; Amr" authorityYear="2003" box="[240,749,1700,1725]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Jaculus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="jaculus">
<emphasis box="[240,416,1700,1725]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Jaculus jaculus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation box="[434,741,1700,1725]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref30180" refString="Abu Baker, M. &amp; Amr, Z. (2003 a) A morphometric and taxonomic revision of the genus Gerbillus in Jordan with notes on its current distribution. Zoologische Abhandlungen (Dresden), 53, 177 - 204." type="journal article">Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2003a</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. It was collected from Al Jafr and Al Mudawwarah area in southern Jordan and was also associated with the sand jird (Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2004).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,1484,1941]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1772,1797]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Remarks</emphasis>
: In coloration and skull proportions, this species is identical to 
<emphasis box="[1027,1166,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">G. h. mariae</emphasis>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1236,1295,1772,1797]" name="Syria" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Syria</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref30180" refString="Abu Baker, M. &amp; Amr, Z. (2003 a) A morphometric and taxonomic revision of the genus Gerbillus in Jordan with notes on its current distribution. Zoologische Abhandlungen (Dresden), 53, 177 - 204." type="journal article">Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2003a</bibRefCitation>
). It differs from 
<emphasis box="[512,657,1808,1833]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">G. h. jordani</emphasis>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[728,811,1808,1833]" name="Tunisia" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Tunisia</collectingCountry>
by being more grayish and having the gray hair bases longer. This conclusion is also shared by Harrison &amp; Bates (1991). 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Winton" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[933,1047,1844,1869]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="henleyi">
<emphasis box="[933,1047,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">G. henleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows a 2N=52 and FN=62. The karyotype includes 8 submetacentric and 42 acrocentric autosomes. The X and Y are large and medium sized submetacentric chromosomes, respectively (
<bibRefCitation box="[647,908,1916,1941]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref30364" refString="Abu Baker, M., Khalil, A., Sheyab, F. &amp; Amr, Z. (2009) A karyotypic study on rodents of the genus Gerbillus collected from Jordan. Vertebrate Zoology, 59 (1), 111 - 116." type="journal article">
Abu Baker 
<emphasis box="[777,825,1916,1941]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">et al</emphasis>
., 2009
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
